subSection.paragraph:
Adult habitus
. Body color brown to dark brown (
Fig. 1a
). Head brown to dark brown with yellow spots: ocellar spot diamond-shaped, frontal spot anterior to median ocellus larger and subquadrate with three small serrations along the anterior edge, yellow area of occiput sometimes hidden by pronotum. Antennae and palpi variable; both brown on younger specimens while in aged adults the antennae are black and much darker than palpi (
Fig. 1a
). The lateral sides of pronotum parallel, but sometimes the posterior portion is moderately widened (
Figs. 1a–b
); median pronotal stripe yellow, consisting of an inverted triangular anterior portion and a rectangular posterior portion.

Paraproct sclerite triangular and curved apically (
Figs. 3b–c
). The fully everted paraproct lobe is thumb-shaped, enlarged and extends laterally at mid-length abruptly curved dorsolaterally and covered with brown scales (
Figs. 3a–f
); epiproct globular, with brown dorsal tiny spinules and hairs (
Figs. 3c–d
).

Aedeagus membranous, short, wide, and multilobed, with an unpaired dorsal lobe and two pairs of lateral lobes (
Figs. 4–5
). The anterodorsal lobe large and conical, posterodorsal lobe smaller and nipple-like, the latter located medially between the anterolateral lobes. Each anterolateral lobe is smaller and shorter than posterolateral lobe, the lobe anteriorly and dorsally curved, generally nipple-like. Each posterolateral lobe partly everted in the field (
Figs. 4a–d
), extended laterally, round to elliptical in ventral view, similarly shaped as anterolateral lobe in caudal view; when fully everted, the lobe greatly extended posteriorly forming a large medially curved tube, apex enlarged and trilobed (
Figs. 4e–f
, 
5a–d
).
